    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1259048086" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1259048086" />
    <a title="Vampire Who Baked" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/40429778-vampire-who-baked"><img alt="Vampire Who Baked" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1424496524p2/40429778.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1259048086?book_show_action=true">Apr 19, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Vampire Who Baked" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Vampire Who Baked" href="/user/show/40429778-vampire-who-baked">Vampire Who Baked</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/40429778-vampire-who-baked?shelf=favourites">favourites</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/40429778-vampire-who-baked?shelf=situated-stories">situated-stories</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/40429778-vampire-who-baked?shelf=treasures">treasures</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1259048086" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1325088419525605915">&quot;Here the Sea ends and the Earth begins.&quot; Somehow, this line never comes up in any of those numerous lists on the Internet, of memorable, or meaningful, opening lines. Which is a pity, since Saramago is an equal to Camus (&apos;The Stranger&apos;) or Tolstoy (&apos;Anna Karenina&apos;) when it comes to defining a book by a single line, perhaps not in terms of story (like Tolstoy) or tone (like Camus), but there&apos;s this je ne sais quoi associated with this line, and the line after that &quot;It is raining over the colourl</span>
  <span id="freeText1325088419525605915" style="display:none">"Here the Sea ends and the Earth begins." Somehow, this line never comes up in any of those numerous lists on the Internet, of memorable, or meaningful, opening lines. Which is a pity, since Saramago is an equal to Camus ('The Stranger') or Tolstoy ('Anna Karenina') when it comes to defining a book by a single line, perhaps not in terms of story (like Tolstoy) or tone (like Camus), but there's this je ne sais quoi associated with this line, and the line after that "It is raining over the colourless city", that your reaction to these opening lines will perhaps tell you how you shall respond to the rest of the text.<br /><br />Comparing Saramago (as one always does) with the limited set of authors I have read, I am tempted to write Saramago = Kundera + Bruno Schulz + Calvino. For like Kundera, he can delight you and move you and take your breath away with insightful commentaries on the human condition, and convince you that his philosophy is the only reality that exists. Like Bruno Schulz, he can weave fantastic imagery within an exquisite filigree of wordplay and metaphor to make you live through the eyes of a blind man who gains sight just for a moment to see a rainbow for the first time. Like Calvino he is an astounding storyteller, and he can leave you in the grips of his text, turning page after page in a way that it frenetic while at the same time languid, while in truth very little is really happening on the pages themselves.<br /><br />I realise I was mistaken in writing Saramago = Kundera + Bruno Schulz + Calvino. It's actually the other way round, Kundera = Saramago - Schulz - Calvino, and similar for the rest, because on readint this book one realises that it's not that Saramago combines the virtues in these authors, but that these authors lack the sensibility and skill in Saramago. <br /><br />Saramago's writing is notorious for its frugal use of punctuation, restricting to commas and period and eschewing everything else - hyphens, semi-colons, exclamation marks, even quotes and question marks- in the entire text. It is also notorious for having sentences spanning pages. This only makes it all the more remarkable that this abstruse style is not only coherent, it is the most <i>apt</i> style for the kind of narrative Saramago weaves- take this away and the book diminishes from sublime perfection to the nothingness of mediocrity. Saramago's "reality" is multilayered and immediate, and one has to read this book to understand that Time does not stop for semicolons and hyphens to show up.<br /><br />If you know a bit of a backstory about Portuguese literature (specifically Fernando Pessoa and his <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heteronym_(literature)" rel="nofollow noopener"> heteronyms </a>, you will realise that this style has a dual purpose in the context of this book. One of the key effects of this narrative style is that when an entire conversation is separated only by commas and the occasional capitalisation, it is easy to lose track of who is saying what. This is absolutely perfect for the conversations between Ricardo Reis and the ghost of Fernanco Pessoa- since Reis is simply a heteronym of Pessoa, when Ricardo and Fernando are conversing it is really as if a single person is having a conversation with himself, and demarcations that define who is speaking at any given point are therefore meaningless.<br /><br />At this point, it is apt to commend the translator who has beautifully assimilated Saramago to the English language. It really is a pity that the translator's is a job that is little recognised as a form of art in itself, considering how much skill one has to have with words and wordplay, and how much familiarity with both the languages and the cultures one is translating from (for culture can in no way separated from language, and must be translated just like the words themselves; it is only fitting, and even due, to appreciate the superior sensibility that ends the book exactly where it began, "where the Sea ends and the Earth awaits".</span>
  <a data-text-id="1325088419525605915" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


