<div id="review_3071733702" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3071733702" />
    <a title="Bob" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/82944-bob"><img alt="Bob" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1502065904p2/82944.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3071733702?book_show_action=true">Dec 03, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Bob" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Bob" href="/user/show/82944-bob">Bob</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780156996938" href="/book/show/588526.The_Year_of_the_Death_of_Ricardo_Reis">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3071733702" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4099473132908680334">Saramago is strong in all the usual novelistic ways of well-developed characters, detailed places and eras, but also frequently employs some &quot;high concept&quot; premise (&quot;everyone in the city temporarily goes blind&quot;, for example).<br/><br/>In this case, the title character returns to Lisbon after a lengthy expatriation in Brazil on hearing of the death of his old friend, the poet Fernando Pessoa. What he discovers on arrival is that everyone has a nine-month period of their afterlife (analogous to their gestat</span>
  <span id="freeText4099473132908680334" style="display:none">Saramago is strong in all the usual novelistic ways of well-developed characters, detailed places and eras, but also frequently employs some "high concept" premise ("everyone in the city temporarily goes blind", for example).<br /><br />In this case, the title character returns to Lisbon after a lengthy expatriation in Brazil on hearing of the death of his old friend, the poet Fernando Pessoa. What he discovers on arrival is that everyone has a nine-month period of their afterlife (analogous to their gestation) in which they can appear as what we would call a ghost to whomever they choose.<br /><br />This magical realist subplot winds in and out of the story, but the heart of it is the influx of refugees (many of them aristocrats) from the Spanish Civil War and the subtler menace of the recently initiated dictatorship of Portugal under Salazar (slightly preceding Franco).<br /><br />Reis, a physician who left the country a couple of decades prior, begins to the attract the attention of the authorities and we are never clear if he actually did anything or harbored political opinions to merit the scrutiny. Another large part of the story is his affair with a hotel chambermaid - nothing in any intellectual, spiritual or emotional experience he undergoes alters the deep social divide between them and she seems not to expect it.<br /><br />Finally, the book won't tell you this, but little research is needed to find that "Ricardo Reis" was one of many pseudonyms employed by Fernando Pessoa. Saramago has taken a sort of historical footnote and written a "backstory" for the character, somewhat comparable to "Wide Sargasso Sea".</span>
  <a data-text-id="4099473132908680334" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


